frequent_values: This school year we offered dance, movement, music and visual arts to our students. We believe performing arts and visual arts are essential in a students education. Our goal is to enhance socialization, academic achievement and boost self-esteem. The arts department is aligned with the Common Core Standards as well as the Blue Prints for the Arts. Students are exposed to different dance forms, line dance, yoga, cultural dance, ballroom and role play in dance and movement. In visual arts, students learn about famous artists and how to use their techniques. In collaboration with several arts residency programs, students have the opportunity to gain valuable skills in music, dance, theater and art literacy while learning to work together as a team and gaining experience in performing live in front of an audience. Students use their voice and instruments during music and have the opportunity to perform at Carnegie Hall. We offer many opportunities to be involved during school and after school in our arts programs. We have performances during the school day as well as in the evenings. The arts department allows students to use creativity, imagination and collaboration to increase confidence, focus and perseverance in each discipline

Frank McCourt High School provides all students with a two-year introduction to visual art and dance.  Our 9th and 10th grade Media curriculum provides students with an understanding of visual art techniques and building blocks that can be expanded upon in elective courses and applied in media work throughout the disciplines.  Dance is introduced through our Physical Education program- including movement and choreography- to all students and interested students can elect to take specific dance courses in 11th and 12th grades.  In addition, we have a robust opt-in arts program that includes visual art, dance, theater and music.  Community arts organizations and campus teachers work with our teachers to provide opportunities and instruction to all interested students.  We celebrate the arts at our school annually in an Art Show that includes gallery and performance displays.
We currently offer blueprint reading and writing for students enrolled in our construction trades, and have an extensive architecture program for students enrolled in our Architecture program.

This year we Worked with Arts Horizon. Arts Horizon supplied excellent music/dance field trips for our elementary and middle schools and our High School received the artist in residency programs. We are grateful our students were able to participate and learn from such professionals. Vital components of the arts are put into practice at P993 on a consistent and daily basis. From listening skills to eye hand coordination, to peer interaction in dance and theater, students are actively engaged in best practices. The arts are an active component of the core curriculum; from poetry to Math in Music. The arts engage students by allowing them to describe and evaluate their works of art. That is why we at P.993Q cherish our connection with various arts related activities, performances, etc.

This exposure facilitate students to exposure to the elements of arts.  Students are also exposed to Dancing, Vocal Music, Instruments (Drumming).

Goals: To provide instruction to all students in dance, music, theater and visual arts. To continue integration of the arts into subject curriculum through a variety of initiatives. To provide enrichment opportunities through clubs that support college and career readiness. E.g. Broadcast Journalism Team, Audio/Visual Team. To provide information for students and families about arts opportunities available locally and throughout NYC. To create community connections through the arts. E.g.; student performances at local senior centers. To expose students to a variety of arts experiences. Our school based programs include: DANCE: •Collaborate with music and theater teachers on choreography for class plays in grades 3, 4 and 5 •Dance Club in grades 4 & 5 •Preparation of children in all grades for school wide celebrations. MUSIC: Vocal and Instrumental •Grades K-5 served •Grades 4&5 classes rework known songs for class plays •Recorder in grades 2 & 3 •chorus• band •accordion band •winter and spring concerts •All students prepared for performances in school-wide presentations. THEATER:•All grades served • Grades 4 & 5 classroom teachers work with theater and music specialists to create an original 40 minute musical play• Other grades receive theater arts skills instruction • Produce full-length Drama Club musical. VISUAL ARTS: •All grades 3-5 classes create their own scenery for class plays.
GOAL: to connect families with their child's education through ongoing opportunities in the arts that support student achievement.

This year was another exciting year of art for students at PS 15, as we continue to expand our programs and partners (adding Puppetry this year). In addition, through implementation of the School-wide Enrichment Model, the faculty and staff have played an integral part in providing sustainable arts programming based on student-interest in clusters such as “Art for Change,” “Photography,” “Making Music” and “Trash to Treasure”. 
We continued residency programs with organizations such as The Children's Museum of Art, Mark DeGarmo Dance and Third Street Music, in which kindergarten through fifth grade students learned through the Orff Shulwerk approach. Students explored basic rhythms/melodies using various instruments. 
All our students visited arts museums, films and performances to supplement and extend arts learning objectives grown out of classroom curriculum. We continued our nine-year relationship with Arts for All, Inc, providing our kindergarten through second grade students with opportunities to integrate theater and visual art into literacy. Our students have many opportunities to express themselves through dance, music, and theater with our partnerships with Mark DeGarmo Dance, Rosie’s Broadway Kids, puppetry with Arts Connection and creative storytelling with Story Pirates. Lastly, through our Technology Arts class, students study mentor artists, learn coding, graphic design, and animation. We expect to have many submissions to this year’s District 1 Arts Fair and close the year on a high note for Arts at PS 15!

PS 221 prides itself on arts education. Our programs include visual arts, musical, and dance instruction. Our music program includes singing, performing, Orff, recorder, guitar, ukulele, and drums. We perform in school concerts and community outreach. Our 4th grade performs a holiday concert, 3rd grade a recorder concert, & 2nd grade Earth friendly songs at our Science Fair. This year we performed for the Queensboro president’s office during the winter holidays. We also have group of fifth graders in our North Hills Harmonics. Our visual arts program includes 5th grade sketchbooks, art history, and a partnership with Deepdale Cares. This year’s community project created artwork for our school atrium and their coop community. Together students and Deepdale Cares seniors worked painted terracotta pots, stepping stones, and birdhouses. We also have ‘Artify It!’, an art enrichment program. Our students participate in the Square 1 visual arts project. Our dance program includes Dancing Classrooms and our annual Dance Festival. Our theatre experiences included Circus Arts, Marathon Playhouse, Queens Theater, LeAP, and the Queens Museum. Our visual arts experiences included the MET. This year’s residencies programs were Journeys into American Indian Territory and the Art Works Project with visits to the MET. In-house, our annual Renaissance program incorporates a wide variety of enrichment experiences in the arts, such as dance, theater, visual arts, and music. We hold an annual talent show, Family Art Night and an Open Mic event.

At the Curious Young Learners Pre-K center, we believe curiosity leads the children down new paths. At the cornerstone of our school is our arts program. Children are naturally creative and derive much pleasure from involvement in the arts. They learn a host of skills and acquire tremendous self-esteem when given varied opportunities to create. Because we consider art such an integral part of our program, our children are provided with open-ended opportunities to create. Our children use a wide array of art media including acrylic, finger, and water paints, pastels, crayons, and markers. In addition, children are given the opportunity to express themselves through drawings, sculptures, models, and paintings. 
We celebrate our children’s creativity by prominently and artfully displaying their work throughout our preschool sweet. Because we believe the artistic process to be even more valuable than the final product, we accompany each work with a transcription of the child’s thoughts about the piece along with pictures of the process.
The children participate with increasing interest and enjoyment in a variety of music activities including listening to music, singing songs, performing finger plays and experimenting with various musical instruments. We encourage the children by creating sounds using traditional instruments like bells, drums, and recorders. In addition, the children use some non-traditional instruments that we make out of tin cans, oatmeal boxes and cardboard containers. Singing songs, making up silly and rhym

P.S.54 is a Pre-K through 5 school which is dedicated to providing school wide arts programs which enable our students to express themselves through music, visual arts and theater. Our school includes extracurricular areas in these areas as well. All of our art classes provide opportunities for active participation. The Visual Arts program follows the NYC DOE blueprint for Teaching and Learning in Visual Arts. Final products are published on Artsonia, which is an online Art Museum. P.S. 54’s music program serves grades Pre-Kindergarten through Fifth Grade. Grades Pre-K and K receive Music and Movement which includes movement activities, small percussion and singing. Grades 1, 2, and 3 receive either recorder class, vocal class, or keyboard class depending on scheduling and location. Grades 4 and 5 are Modern Band guitar classes.Students in grades Pre K through 2 are working towards mastering the Benchmarks for Theater by activating and using their imaginations and exploring the use of the actor’s tools – body, voice and imagination. Using literacy as their source, students participate in group, partner and individual activities which include dramatic play, storytelling, puppetry, music, and dance. All activities are embedded in the ELA CCSS for the appropriate grade level. Students in grades 3 through 5 are working towards mastering the Benchmarks for Theater for Grade 5. Students exercise and refine the actor’s instrument—the body, voice and mind—through ongoing exploration of the physical, vocal, characterization.

Due to continued space constraints in the building, our greenhouse serves as a music room . With no dedicated auditorium, performances are staged in our all-purpose room that houses our lunchroom as well as space where physical education conducted.

Rockaway Collegiate High School is a small school serving approximately 390 students from primarily economically disadvantaged communities.  About 75% of our students qualify for free lunch and 85% qualify for free or reduced lunch.  56% of our student body are males and most of our student population is comprised of blacks and Hispanics.  We are a community school that offers many services to our students and their families to support the student’s social emotional development as well as meet their academic needs.  Our students are extremely creative and talented and would benefit from a culturally rich arts program.  They are also fortunate to have a committed and dedicated staff that work collectively to understand their needs and meet their demands on a daily basis.

At P.S. 171, our classroom teachers have worked diligently to incorporate the arts into their classroom teaching of multiple subjects.  Music, visual arts and movement are all utilized in order to capitalize on different student learning styles.

Presently we have a Century 21 Grant in which the students participate in multiple activities.  Students receive the following:
Martial Arts, Vocal Music, (FYREZONE), Drum Line and Entrepreneurship.
Students in grades 6-8 participate in the above activities.

Throught the expolration of a variety media- drawings, collage, painting, and now theater, Ps 138 is helping students develop an understanding of the principal of art and the elements of design. Students are able to use academic art language to discuss artworks and always cite "visual evidence" to support inferences, claim, and arguments made about a work of art. Goal 1: To increase student's awareness of Visual arts. 1)Introcuce different artist, art element, principles of design, and art forms to students.Goal 2: To demonstrade and develop Arts methods that support students achievement. Goal 3:To educate students about art, as well as celebrate students's creativity.This year,PS 138 partner with The New Victory theater to enhance art instruction in the middle school. Our school is committed to providing our students with a rich and diverse arts experience. This experience includes exposure to all arts disciplines, integration of art into the instructional program and exposure to all of our city's art rich cultural institutions and resources. Our students learn to appreciate art in their environment and they understand how art contributes to their lives. Our teachers are also committed to art learning through ongoing professional development offered throughout the year. They integrate visual arts into all subject areas and help students explore their creative talents in a variety of disciplines including visual arts, drama, music, dance and technology. We have great arts partnerships that help us to provide students with rich experience in all of the above. We provide music exposure and learning to all of our early childhood students and we offer instrumental music instruction in woodwinds, percussion and violin to students in third through eighth grade. Our goal moving forward is to grow our art program so that there is cumulative learning in visual arts and music in pre-kindergarten through eighth grade and to integrate theater arts into the middle school curriculum so that there is alignment to content area learning. We also seek additional funds for instruction in  visual arts on every grade.  "Excellence, Engagement and Enrichment" is our mission statement and we are committed to offering our students a well rounded arts experience utilizing our school and city resources.

The Arts program at Philippa Schyuler Middle School for the Gifted & Talented has been one of our prized jewels for many years! This versatile program offers students the opportunity to study a variety of disciplines. From Modern and Urban dance to Steel Pan and Concert Band, our students are immersed in learning activities that afford them the chance to express themselves and showcase their many talents in a multitude of ways. This year, one of our school's goals has been to continue to enrich and expand the Performing & Visual Arts program within our school community. 

Given this focus, we have boosted our level of performance, and expanded both of our annual winter and spring concerts to encompass more diversity and theatrical elements. We also put together an elaborate production of the theatrical play, Antigone, with full cast and crew! We have also expanded on our International Day celebrations to include more performance opportunities that highlight a variety of cultures. In addition, we have created partnerships with local Arts Educational programs to prepare our students with the foundational skills needed to succeed in these realms. Through these comprehensive programs, students learn valuable, life-long skills that are necessary to working in large and diverse groups. Additionally, they broaden the scope of our school community, allowing for teachers, students and parents to come together and acknowledge the hard work and diligence found within our Performing and Visual Arts Program.
